Several cathode types have been explored, including carbonaceous materials [84] (such as graphite, vitreous carbon, carbon felt) [78], oxygen diffusion cathodes [115], and boron-doped diamond electrode [49], which can be used for satisfactory electrochemical production of H2O2. In a PEC system, H2O2 can act as electron acceptor, thus preventing the recombination of e−/h+ pairs and causing decomposition into hydroxyl radicals (H2O2 + e−CB → OH− + ●OH). Due to the instability and risk involved in the transportation and storage of H2O2, it can be produced by the cathodic reduction of oxygen on the counter electrode [116] in acid solutions (Eq. 7) and in alkaline solutions (Eq. 8):7O2+2H++2e−→H2O2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
